From 2eba349f4d072441f62cede0516613d24e0f6f81 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jake Teton-Landis <just.1.jake@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 05:02:47 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 20/25] runInBatch: schedule updates into a live batch's own
 lane
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

unstable_runInBatch(token, fn) — cosignal spec §4.1 fact 4, capability
bit 1<<6. fn's updates are attributed to the token's batch: a live
deferred token pins a transition to the batch's lane (a dedicated
requestTransitionLane override, leaving the event's own transition-lane
bookkeeping untouched); a live urgent token runs fn at the lane's event
priority; a retired/unknown token takes the documented urgent (discrete)
fallback. Nested calls compose and restore. Calling during render throws
(error 605); commit-phase and yield-gap calls are legal, including inside
the onRenderPassYield listener (emitted after the render context pops).

Seam consequence pinned along the way: a mid-render delivery on the
rendering lane lets React commit the completed tree without the delivered
update (interleaved-update semantics) — the finish edge now reports that
commit's rendered writes as a committed-view advance on the root (delta +
committedRoots lock-in, batch stays pending) instead of an empty delta
that would desynchronize per-root committed tables from the visible tree.
The render-time entangled expansion is stashed per root so mid-flight
entanglements (updates not in the committed tree) stay out of the report.

Tests: ReactFiberRunInBatch-test.js (10) — spec tests 18/19, the torn
control, yield-edge listener delivery, urgent-fallback preemption pin,
render-phase throw, nested restore, layout-effect delivery re-report,
retiring-commit outgoing-token window, and the test-24 insertion
interplay. All four channels green; 15 upstream suites green; linc, flow
dom-node, prettier, extract-errors clean.
